You can specify normals for faces you create. This is a vector that's perpendicular to the face. Specifying normals is important if you plan to use lighting. They tell OpenGL how the light is to be reflected. Although OpenGL is not a raytracer, it still influences how bright you see the face. OpenGL will not calculate the normals itself, you have to do it manually.

== Specifying Normals ==
Normals are specified using the function ''glNormal3f'' and used before you make the vertices that belong to the face. Example:

 // Create a square on the XY axis. The normal vector is then (0, 0, 1)
 glBegin(GL_QUADS);
     glNormal3f(0.0, 0.0, 1.0);
     glVertex3f(0.0, 0.0, 0.0);
     glVertex3f(0.0, 1.0, 0.0);
     glVertex3f(1.0, 1.0, 0.0);
     glVertex3f(1.0, 0.0, 0.0);
 glEnd();

== Calculating Normals ==
There is a quite simple approach for calculating the normal vector for a triangle. Given ''p1'', ''p2'' and ''p3'', the normal vector can be expressed as the cross product of (p2 - p1) and (p3 - p1), divided by the length of the result. In C code, using a struct type for the vectors:

 struct vector a, b, n;
 double l;

 a.x = p2.x - p1.x;
 a.y = p2.y - p1.y;
 a.z = p2.z - p1.z;

 b.x = p3.x - p1.x;
 b.y = p3.y - p1.y;
 b.z = p3.z - p1.z;

 n.x = (a.y * b.z) - (a.z * b.y);
 n.y = (a.z * b.x) - (a.x * b.z);
 n.z = (a.x * b.y) - (a.y * b.x);

 // Normalize (divide by root of dot product)
 l = sqrt(n.x * n.x + n.y * n.y + n.z * n.z);
 n.x /= l;
 n.y /= l;
 n.z /= l;

 // Now pass n.x, n.y, n.z to glNormal3f

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{FULLCHAPTERNAME}}]]

== The pathophysiology and neurobiology of Bipolar Disorder == == Role of specific neurotransmitters in Bipolar Disorder ==
== Dopamine ==
Dopamine pathways in the midbrain help to regulate motor activity, motivation and reward circuits. Behavioral changes of the manic phase such as increase in goal-directed behavior and excitement may involve these dopaminergic pathways. Mesolimbic dopaminergic pathways may be directly involved in the selection and coordination of goal-directed behavior, especially those elicted by reward stimuli. Homovanillic acid (HVA), a metabolite of dopamine, is reduced in the cerebral spinal fluid (CSF) of some depressed patients. Conversely, CSF levels of HVA are increased in some manic patients.{{ref|Goodwin2007}} Pharmacological agents which act on the dopamine pathways further implicate dopamine in the pathogenesis of bipolar symptoms. The dopamine precursor L-dopa can produce hypomania in bipolar patients. Amphetamine, which promotes dopamine release can cause hypomania in bipolar patients and can induce hypomanic symptoms in normal people. Bromocriptine and piribedil, which are direct dopamine agonists exhibit antidepressant properties and cause mania in some bipolar patients. Conversely, neuroleptics which block dopamine receptors have antimanic properties.{{ref|Goodwin2007}} Pramipexole, a dopamine agonist at the D2/D3 site, shows antidepressant efficacy as an augmentation strategy in Bipolar patients who are failing treatment with mood stabilizers.{{ref|Goodwin2007}}
===References=== # {{note|Goodwin2007}}Goodwin, F.K. and Jamison, K.R., "Manic-Depressive Illness", 2007., p.482 # {{note|Goodwin2007}}Goodwin, F.K. and Jamison, K.R., "Manic-Depressive Illness", 2007., p.484 # {{note|Goodwin2007}}Goodwin, F.K. and Jamison, K.R., "Manic-Depressive Illness", 2007., p.486 {{cite book|last=Goodwin|first=F.K.|last2=Jamison|first2=K.R.|date=2007|title=Manic-Depressive Illness:Bipolar Disorders and Recurrent Depression|edition=2nd| publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195135794}}

