[[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/q-iterations#Julia_set_by_IIM.2FJ|Inverse iteration of repellor for drawing Julia set]]

==Complex potential - Boettcher coordinate ==
[[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/boettcher|See description here]]

==BSM/J==

This algorithm is used when dynamical plane consist of two of more basins of attraction. For example for c=0. 

It is not appropiate when interior of filled Julia set is empty, for example for c=i.

Description of algorithm :
* for every pixel of dynamical plane <math>z</math> do :
** compute 4 corners ( vertices)  of pixel <math>z_{lt} , z_{rt} , z_{rb} , z_{lb} </math> ( where lt denotes left top, rb denotes right bottom, ... )
** check to which basin corner belongs ( standard escape time and bailout test ) 
** if corners do not belong to the same basin mark it as Julia set

Examples of code
* program in Pascal<ref>[http://www.firebaugh.com/FDA/Courses/CS.320/Week.11/Ch11b.www/Ch11b.html Pascal program fo BSM/J by Morris W. Firebaugh]</ref>
* via convolution with a kernel <ref> [http://facstaff.unca.edu/mcmcclur/papers/BoundaryScanPP.pdf Boundary scanning and complex dynamics by Mark McClure]</ref>

==DEM/J==
This algorith has 2 versions :
* exterior
* interior

Compare it with [[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/demm|version for parameter plane and Mandelbrot set : DEM/J]]
===Internal distance estimation===
===External distance estimation===
<gallery>
File:Demj.jpg|c=-0.74543+0.11301*i
File:Julia dem.png| c= -0.75+0.11
File:Demj6.png| c = 0.255
File:Julia dem c=-0.1+0.651.png|c=-0.1+0.651
</gallery>
" For distance estimate it has been proved that the computed value differs from the true distance at most by a factor of 4. " (Wolf Jung)


Math formula :

<math>distance(z_0, K_c, n) = 2 * |z_n| * \frac{log|z_n| }{ |z'_n| }\,</math>

where :


<math>z'_n\,</math> is [[w:Complex_quadratic_polynomial| first derivative with respect to c]].  


This [[w:derivative|derivative]] can be found by [[w:Iterated function|iteration]] starting with 

: <math>z'_0 = 1 \,</math>

and then :

<math>z'_n= 2*z_{n-1}*z'_{n-1}\,</math>





====How to use distance ==== 


One can use distance for colouring  :
* only Julia set ( boundary of filled Julia set)
* boundary and exterior of filled Julia set. 


Here is first example :

 if (LastIteration==IterationMax) 
     then { /*  interior of Julia set, distance = 0 , color black */ }
     else /* exterior or boundary of Filled-in Julia set  */
          {  double distance=give_distance(Z0,C,IterationMax);
             if (distance<distanceMax)
                 then { /*  Julia set : color = white */ }
                 else  { /*  exterior of Julia set : color = black */}
          }

Here is second example <ref>[[Pictures_of_Julia_and_Mandelbrot_Sets/Computer_programs| Pictures of Julia and Mandelbrot sets  by Gert Buschmann]]</ref>

 if (LastIteration==IterationMax) or distance < distanceMax then ... // interior by ETM/J and boundary by DEM/J
 else .... // exterior by real escape time

====Zoom====

DistanceMax is smaller than pixel size. During zooming pixel size is decreasing and DistanceMax should also be decreased to obtain good picture. 
It can be made by using formula :

<math>DistanceMax = \frac{PixelSize}{n} \,</math> 

where <math>n \le  1 \,</math>

One can start with n=1 and increase n if picture is not good. Check also iMax !!

DistanceMax may also be proportional to zoom factor <math>mag\,</math><ref>[[Pictures_of_Julia_and_Mandelbrot_Sets/Computer_programs|Pictures of Julia and Mandelbrot sets by Gert Buschmann]]</ref> :

<math>DistanceMax = \sqrt{\frac {thick}{1000 * mag}}</math>

where thick is image width ( in  world units) and mag is a zoom factor.

====Examples of code ====

For cpp example see mndlbrot::dist  from  mndlbrot.cpp in src code of program [http://mndynamics.com/indexp.html mandel ver 5.3 by Wolf Jung].

C function : 
<source lang =c>
/*based on function  mndlbrot::dist  from  mndlbrot.cpp
 from program mandel by Wolf Jung (GNU GPL )
 http://www.mndynamics.com/indexp.html  */
double jdist(double Zx, double Zy, double Cx, double Cy ,  int iter_max)
 { 
 int i;
 double x = Zx, /* Z = x+y*i */
         y = Zy, 
         /* Zp = xp+yp*1 = 1  */
         xp = 1, 
         yp = 0, 
         /* temporary */
         nz,  
         nzp,
         /* a = abs(z) */
         a; 
 for (i = 1; i <= iter_max; i++)
  { /* first derivative   zp = 2*z*zp  = xp + yp*i; */
    nz = 2*(x*xp - y*yp) ; 
    yp = 2*(x*yp + y*xp); 
    xp = nz;
    /* z = z*z + c = x+y*i */
    nz = x*x - y*y + Cx; 
    y = 2*x*y + Cy; 
    x = nz; 
    /* */
    nz = x*x + y*y; 
    nzp = xp*xp + yp*yp;
    if (nzp > 1e60 || nz > 1e60) break;
  }
 a=sqrt(nz);
 /* distance = 2 * |Zn| * log|Zn| / |dZn| */
 return 2* a*log(a)/sqrt(nzp); 
 }
</source>

Delphi function : 
<syntaxhighlight lang="delphi">

function Give_eDistance(zx0,zy0,cx,cy,ER2:extended;iMax:integer):extended;

var zx,zy ,  // z=zx+zy*i
    dx,dy,  //d=dx+dy*i  derivative :  d(n+1)=  2 * zn * dn
    zx_temp,
    dx_temp,
    z2,  //
    d2, //
    a // abs(d2)
     :extended;
    i:integer;
begin
  //initial values
  // d0=1
  dx:=1;
  dy:=0;
  //
  zx:=zx0;
  zy:=zy0;
  // to remove warning : variables may be not initialised ?
  z2:=0;
  d2:=0;

  for i := 0 to iMax - 1 do
    begin
      // first derivative   d(n+1) = 2*zn*dn  = dx + dy*i;
      dx_temp := 2*(zx*dx - zy*dy) ;
      dy := 2*(zx*dy + zy*dx);
      dx := dx_temp;
      // z = z*z + c = zx+zy*i
      zx_temp := zx*zx - zy*zy + Cx;
      zy := 2*zx*zy + Cy;
      zx := zx_temp;
      //
      z2:=zx*zx+zy*zy;
      d2:=dx*dx+dy*dy;
      if ((z2>1e60) or (d2 > 1e60)) then  break;

    end; // for i
   if (d2 < 0.01) or (z2 < 0.1)  // when do not use escape time
    then  result := 10.0
    else
      begin
        a:=sqrt(z2);
        // distance = 2 * |Zn| * log|Zn| / |dZn|
        result := 2* a*log10(a)/sqrt(d2);
      end;

end;  //  function Give_eDistance
</syntaxhighlight>

Matlab code by Jonas Lundgren<ref>[http://www.mathworks.ch/matlabcentral/fileexchange/27749-julia-sets Julia sets  by Jonas Lundgren   in Matlab]</ref>
<syntaxhighlight lang="matlab">
function D = jdist(x0,y0,c,iter,D)
%JDIST Estimate distances to Julia set by potential function
% by Jonas Lundgren http://www.mathworks.ch/matlabcentral/fileexchange/27749-julia-sets
% Code covered by the BSD License http://www.mathworks.ch/matlabcentral/fileexchange/view_license?file_info_id=27749


% Escape radius^2
R2 = 100^2;

% Parameters
N = numel(x0);
M = numel(y0);
cx = real(c);
cy = imag(c);
iter = round(1000*iter);

% Create waitbar
h = waitbar(0,'Please wait...','name','Julia Distance Estimation');
t1 = 1;

% Loop over pixels
for k = 1:N/2
    x0k = x0(k);
    for j = 1:M
        % Update distance?
        if D(j,k) == 0
            % Start values
            n = 0;
            x = x0k;
            y = y0(j);
            b2 = 1;                 % |dz0/dz0|^2
            a2 = x*x + y*y;         % |z0|^2
            % Iterate zn = zm^2 + c, m = n-1
            while n < iter && a2 <= R2
                n = n + 1;
                yn = 2*x*y + cy;
                x = x*x - y*y + cx;
                y = yn;
                b2 = 4*a2*b2;       % |dzn/dz0|^2
                a2 = x*x + y*y;     % |zn|^2
            end
            % Distance estimate
            if n < iter
                % log(|zn|)*|zn|/|dzn/dz0|
                D(j,k) = 0.5*log(a2)*sqrt(a2/b2);
            end
        end
    end
    % Lap time
    t = toc;
    % Update waitbar
    if t >= t1
        str = sprintf('%0.0f%% done in %0.0f sec',200*k/N,t);
        waitbar(2*k/N,h,str)
        t1 = t1 + 1;
    end
end

% Close waitbar
close(h)
</syntaxhighlight>

[[Maxima]] function :

 GiveExtDistance(z0,c,e_r,i_max):=
 /* needs z in exterior of Kc */
 block(
 [z:z0,
 dz:1,
 cabsz:cabs(z),
 cabsdz:1, /* overflow limit */
 i:0],
 while  cabsdz < 10000000 and  i<i_max
  do 
   (
    dz:2*z*dz,
    z:z*z + c,
    cabsdz:cabs(dz),
    i:i+1
   ),
  cabsz:cabs(z), 
  return(2*cabsz*log(cabsz)/cabsdz)
 )$

==Convergence ==
In this algorithm distances between 2 points of the same orbit are checked

=== average discrete velocity of orbit ===
[[File:Golden Mean Quadratic Siegel Disc Speed.png|right|thumb|average discrete velocity of orbit - code and description]]
It is used in case of :
* [[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/parabolic|parabolic dynamic]]
* [[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/siegel|eliptic dynamic ( Siegel disc )]]

===Cauchy Convergence Algorithm (CCA)===
This algorithm is [http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benutzer:Georg-Johann/Mathematik#Visualising_Julia_sets described] by User:Georg-Johann. Here is also [http://www.bugman123.com/Fractals/index.html Matemathics code by Paul Nylander]

== Normality ==

[[w:normal family |Normality]]
In this algorithm distances between points of 2 orbits are checked



===Checking [[w:equicontinuity|equicontinuity]]  by  Michael Becker===  
"Iteration is equicontinuous on [[w:Fatou set|the Fatou set]] and not on [[w:Julia set|the Julia set]]". (Wolf Jung) <ref>Alan F. Beardon, S. Axler, F.W. Gehring, K.A. Ribet : Iteration of Rational Functions: Complex Analytic Dynamical Systems. Springer, 2000; ISBN 0387951512, 9780387951515; page 49</ref><ref>Joseph H. Silverman : The arithmetic of dynamical systems. Springer, 2007. ISBN 0387699031, 9780387699035; page 22</ref>

Michael Becker compares the distance of two close points under iteration on Riemann sphere.<ref>[[w:de:Benutzer:Georg-Johann/Mathematik | Visualising Julia sets by Georg-Johann]]</ref> 

This method can be used to draw not only Julia sets for polynomials  ( where infinity is always superattracting fixed point) but it can be also  applied  to other functions ( maps), for which infinity is not an attracting fixed point.<ref>[http://www.ijon.de/mathe/julia/some_julia_sets_1_en.html Julia sets by Michael Becker]. See the metric d(z,w)</ref>



=== using Marty's criterion by Wolf Jung ===
Wolf Jung  is using "an alternative method of checking normality, which is based on Marty's criterion:  |f'| / (1 + |f|^2)  must be bounded for all 
iterates." It is implemented in mndlbrot::marty function ( see src code of [http://mndynamics.com/indexp.html program Mandel] ver 5.3 ).
It uses one point of dynamic plane.






== Koenigs coordinate ==

[[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/Koenigs_coordinate|Koenigs coordinate]] are used in the basin of attraction of finite attracting (not superattracting) point (cycle).

